 ----------------------------------------------------------------- 128 1451   11
*****C. Jouanne (Dec. 2015) corrections on Mass and Q reac         128 1451   12
May 2016 : Covariances for total, elastic, (n,2n) and radiative    128 1451   13
capture estimated by BRC based on a brief analysis of experimental 128 1451   14
data. Decay information added for tritium production               128 1451   15
                                                                   128 1451   16
The n-d elastic and breakup cross sections are computed by solving 128 1451   17
the three-body Faddeev equations with the semi-realistic           128 1451   18
MTI-III [Malfliet and Tjon, 1969] and the realistic INOY           128 1451   19
[Dolechall et al., 2003] Nucleon-Nucleon potentials.               128 1451   20
The n-d reaction is considered as a three particle problem         128 1451   21
for nucleons interacting via pairwise potentials and is solved     128 1451   22
by means of the Faddeev equations [Faddeev, 1965].                 128 1451   23
                                                                   128 1451   24
The solution has been obtained numerically by means of             128 1451   25
the standard methods used in the Few-Body problems. They are       128 1451   26
based on a spline expansion of the Faddeev amplitudes              128 1451   27
which transform the set of partial differential equations          128 1451   28
into an homogeneous linear system                                  128 1451   29
[Lazauskas, 2003. Lazauskas and Carbonell, 2005].                  128 1451   30
                                                                   128 1451   31
The cross sections calculated with the INOY potential are          128 1451   32
compared to the existing experimental data and                     128 1451   33
the multiplication factors Keff of heavy water benchmarks          128 1451   34
obtained by Monte Carlo simulations including this evaluation      128 1451   35
can be found in [B.Morillon,R.Lazauskas,J.Carbonell, 2012].        128 1451   36
                                                                   128 1451   37
 ----------------------------------------------------------------- 128 1451   38
                                                                   128 1451   39
Doleschall, I. Borbely, Z. Papp, W. Plessas,                       128 1451   40
Phys. Rev. C 67 (2003) 064005                                      128 1451   41
                                                                   128 1451   42
Faddeev, L.D., 1965. Mathematical Aspects of the Three-Body        128 1451   43
Problem in the Quantum Scattering Theory,                          128 1451   44
Transl. by Israel Program for Scientific Translations              128 1451   45
                                                                   128 1451   46
Lazauskas, R., 2003, PhD Thesis, Universite Joseph Fourier,        128 1451   47
Grenoble http://tel.ccsd.cnrs.fr/documents/archives0/00/00/41/78/. 128 1451   48
                                                                   128 1451   49
Lazauskas, R., Carbonell, J., 2005, Three-neutron resonance        128 1451   50
trajectories for realistic interaction models,                     128 1451   51
Phys. Rev. C71, 044004, nucl-th/0502037.                           128 1451   52
                                                                   128 1451   53
B. Morillon, R. Lazauskas, J. Carbonell                            128 1451   54
Influence of the ab-initio nd cross sections in the critical       128 1451   55
heavy-water benchmarks, Ann. of Nucl. Energy (2012),               128 1451   56
http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.anucene.2012.06.032                    128 1451   57
